UAT for Nintex on our SharePoint Subscription Edition farm covered the full range of workflow actions, including timer and scheduled jobs. Those jobs were created as part of the test cases, since running production timer jobs against the test environment would have triggered live schedules against production. In-place testing of the existing jobs was not technically feasible.
All new timer and scheduled jobs behaved as expected. A subset of migrated jobs was affected by a known Microsoft-side condition previously addressed on SharePoint 2019 via specific configuration. That configuration was legacy to 2019 and not carried into the SE build, as the behaviour was not expected to persist on the new platform. Following Microsoft's reintroduction of the bug in the July update, we encountered it again and have applied a temporary fix per Microsoft's guidance pending their next patch. The issue is contained and there is no ongoing impact.
